Title: North Woods
Author: Daniel       Mason
My Review:
I had a hard time following this book, which made it difficult to appreciate it.

Each chapter reads like a separate story. In some chapters, I began to connect with the characters and settle into the narrative, the chapter would end and move on to, what seemed to me, entirely new cast and situation. I kept waiting for a clear through line, but never found one.

There were songs and letters whose connections to other chapters or to a larger story weren’t clear to me. An early chapter involving a slave “hunter” made me think the novel might focus on slavery, but that thread didn’t continue. Another chapter about two sisters running an apple farm—tragic, lively, and lightly haunted—was especially compelling, and I wished that story had been allowed to evolve.

I pushed on, hoping everything would eventually click. It never did.

Title: Going Infinite: The Rise and Fall of a New Tycoon
Author: Michael   Lewis
My Review:
The ending had a wonderfully accurate and dark metaphor of SBF’s dog potentially doing him in… great tension break / comic relief. In that moment I was at a point of a complicated frustration with everyone from Sam (for making steps forward with EA the undoing it all and with his lack of organization and perhaps lack of I don’t know what…) to the frustration with his colleagues… and the lawyers (John Ray).

Before I make this next comparison I would like to add I just did some brief research and it seems over $7 billion has already been recovered from the FTX liquidation.

What a mess. It absolutely reminds me of Malcom Gladwell’s chapter on Amanda Knox. Knox was a woman wrongfully convicted of murder.

Crypto is new, unfamiliar and its value to most of the world seems to be viewed as another gambling game for affluent societies. It has not yet traversed into a stable currency for lesser developed countries, economists have hoped it will.

SBF is a pod (Seinfeld reference). The convergence of the two with all that money made for a perfect storm.

Unfortunately this storm will set crypto and effective altruism back.

What a story. Honestly I did not rate this 5 stars because it was an easy read. It was not. But I can’t imagine how frustrating it was for the author to try to make sense of this mess. Furthermore, how to organize a narrative with all the disparate pieces they must have witnessed. Thank you for putting in the time.

Title: Homo Deus: A Brief History of Tomorrow
Author: Yuval Noah Harari
My Review:
I like it and glad he wrote it.

Maybe it could have been shorter.

Deus was probably harder to write than Sapiens. Sapiens was packed with facts and fluid story telling.
Deus 1) beat us with questions about consciousness vs algorithm then 2) tried to peek into how things might play out for humanity as algorithms/data evolve. And for the latter, I wonder the difficulty and second guessing Harari might have went through to put into words.

I want to thank Harari for Deus after Sapiens. It’s refreshing and a gift to us to have someone that is clearly knowledgeable of human history to observe what is quickly happening in front of us, and try to makes sense it.

I sense Harari holds a fairly neutral perspective of past and future. He doesn’t romanticize any period in history or hold strong attachments to how things should be. He executed Deus as a very good thought experiment.

My Review:

Title: The Midnight Library (The Midnight World, #1)
Author: Matt Haig
My Review: An easy read, never a dull moment. Author always picks the right time to add a little twist or pivot in the story to keep you interested. This hero’s journey is all about searching for life’s meaning. Moral for me: you won’t be happy with your life if it’s just given to you. If you build it, your connection is far greater. The protagonist finds things wrong with different lives she tests out. But I think if she grew into any of the lives she tested she could’ve loved them. The problem was her lack of connection made each lives flaws so apparent and hard for her to accept.
